@Jen moody
I would say as long as you get a good chunk of cauliflower it should be fine- the concept of wedges with the core is to hold them together while blanching. You could easily just gather large florets together( use a spider or slotted spoon to get them out of the water). I don’t think it will make any difference in the final outcome. 
Sounds good!

@Ñame,
I agree that streamlining the prep is what people without cleanup staff do.  I managed to get by with just the cast iron skillet, a bowl, and a small baking sheet.  Instead of using a saucepan+ strainer + bowl, I microwaved the greens in a bowl with 1/2 cup of broth.  After removing some greens to a baking sheet, I used a stick blender to purée. 
Next time I might skip separating the greens, just purée them all and toss a few pine nuts on top for texture.

@Terry

I’d try almond extract, if you’re ok to use that. 

Or, you could try squeezing on a little lemon juice, perhaps, or maybe a drizzle of pomegranate molasses? Maybe add some raspberries? I think the purpose of the rum is to make a more complex flavor than just peaches by themselves.

